Motion Picture Prediction Project (MP3)

Daniel Luo, William Peng

Introduction

In todays busy world, media and entertainment exists in spades, yet time is an ever valuable commodity. When you open up Netflix or browse the movie catalogue for newly released movies, youre flooded with a sea of recommendations that leaves your head spinning. Worse - the old adage dont knock it till you try it remains true; how are you supposed to know exactly what you like if you havent seen it before? Luckily for you, were here to offer a solution never seen before - a revolutionary new way to experience movies - the Motion Picture Prediction Project (MP3).

The inspiration behind the MP3 stems from the need for a better recommendation system that deals with hard numbers and insights and understands the needs of the consumer. Compared to other algorithmic recommendation platforms such as Netflix, we arent swayed by potential sponsorships and accept no substitutions when it comes to the quality of our recommendations. We also go beyond the simple figures of movie databases such as IMDb by providing estimated ratings for movies that havent even been released using metrics including average rating, movie budget, production companies, spoken languages, and more. This allows our algorithm to accomplish two things - one, it allows users to sort through our massive database of pre-existing movies to filter out the best quality movies based on their preferences, but also allows us to predict the success of future movies (measured in revenue generation and movie rating scores) letting the user know whether the hype is justified or not.

Data Collection

The dataset used for this project comes from a Kaggle dataset titled Full TMDB Movies Dataset 2024 (1M Movies), authored by user asaniczka. It contains 1.13 million+ movies collected from TMDB (The Movie Database). Some advantages of TMDB over other traditional movie databases is that its community sourced, which means ratings are community driven and less focused on independent reviewers (Rotten Tomatoes, IMDb). TMDB also excels in a variety of movie data, spanning multiple genres and languages, which allows our model to have a wide selection of data points. TMDB also has an excellent Open API, which allows the initial database to be compiled by the author, who maintains and updates the database daily. The reason we chose this dataset is because it includes a variety of features that would be significant indicators of a movie's rating and popularity, like a robust keyword tagging system, budget, ratings, and popularity score. After downloading the dataset, we were able to store the information as a pandas dataframe for further analysis.

Scaling and Transformations

Because our numerical features have very different ranges of values, we will want to scale some of them.

But before we can scale, a lot of our data is skewed, so we will want to transform them first and then scale.

Revenue, budget, popularity, and vote_count are all likely right skewed data as can be seen by comparing their mean and median from the summary statistics above. So we will log scale them.

In[15]:
# Transform columns using np.log1p to reduce skewness
clean_df[['revenue', 'budget', 'popularity', 'vote_count']] = clean_df[['revenue', 'budget', 'popularity', 'vote_count']].apply(lambda x: np.log1p(x))

Now we can scale using the RobustScaler except for revenue, this will be handled differently. This is less effected by outliers which are present in all of them.

In[16]:
rob_scaler = RobustScaler()
In[17]:
# Scale the mentioned columns
clean_df[['budget', 'popularity', 'vote_count']] = rob_scaler.fit_transform(clean_df[['budget', 'popularity', 'vote_count']])

Since revenue and vote average are our target variables and are extremely zero inflated, we will scale them using MinMaxScaler. This will keep the zero-values as zero while also preventing exploding gradients from the huge numbers in revenue. We want to keep the zero-values at zero because of the classification that we will be doing.

Data Exploration

Wilcoxon Rank-Sum Test

We want to know what kind of missing these text based columns have (whether it is Missing Completely at Random, Missing at Random, or Missing Not at Random). We suspect that it is Missing at Random, with the columns mostly relating to the revenue value. A movie which earned more revenue had more people who saw the movie, and thus there are more people who would have filled in the information for these other features in the database that we got our data from.

Now we will take a look at what the distribution of our revenue data looks like to help determine what kind of test we can use.

The significant amount of zeroes with the nonzero values much further off to the right means that any hypothesis test that assumes normality would not be optimal. In this case, we will instead use the Wilcoxon Rank-Sum Test, a non-parametric test for independent samples. Since we want to know if revenue is higher when values are not missing, we will be performing a right-tailed test.

This gives us the following hypotheses:

H0: The median revenue is the same whether the given column is missing a value or not.

HA: The median revenue is higher when the given column is not missing a value.

We will set our alpha level at 0.05.

In[31]:
alpha = 0.05

We only want to test columns that have missing values. Since we dropped the missing values from title and original_language, we don't need to test those columns.

In[32]:
columns_to_test = [
    'keywords',
    'production_companies',
    'production_countries',
    'spoken_languages',
    'genres',
    'overview'
]
In[33]:
for column in columns_to_test:
    print(f"HYPOTHESIS TEST FOR COLUMN: '{column}'")
    # print(f"{clean_df['revenue'].isna().sum()}\t{clean_df[column].isna().sum()}")

    revenue_not_empty = clean_df[~(clean_df[column].isna()) & (clean_df['revenue'] != 0)]['revenue']

    revenue_empty = clean_df[(clean_df[column].isna()) & (clean_df['revenue'] != 0)]['revenue']

    stat, p_value = mannwhitneyu(revenue_not_empty, revenue_empty, alternative='greater')
    
    print(f"  Statistic: {stat}")
    print(f"  P-value: {p_value:.6f}")

The p-values of 0.00000 are significantly under our alpha level of 0.05. This provides significant evidence that we can reject the null hypothesis.

From these hypothesis tests, we have very strong evidence that revenue is higher when there is not a missing value in a text column compared to when there is a missing value. This shows that the missing values in these text columns is Missing at Random. The reason they are missing is related to other observed values (in this case, revenue) in the data.

This means that we cannot just discard rows with missing text data. Instead, we will fill them in with empty strings. This will let the model know that the value was missing.

In[34]:
clean_df[['keywords', 'production_companies', 'production_countries', 'spoken_languages', 'genres', 'overview']] = clean_df[['keywords', 'production_companies', 'production_countries', 'spoken_languages', 'genres', 'overview']].fillna('')

Chi-Square Test of Independence (Genres vs Production Country)

Given that many countries are widely known for being good at making specific genres of movies, the US has Hollywood, famous for producing big-budget action and adventure films, or Japan, famous for its animation (anime), it seems likely that genre and production_countries are not independent. Since these features are categorical, we will use the Chi-Square Test of Independence with the following hypotheses:

H0: The primary genre of a movie and its primary production_country are independent.

HA: The primary genre of a movie and its primary production_country are dependent.

We will again use an alpha of 0.05.

In[35]:
alpha = 0.05

We are testing using the "primary" genre and production country. What this means here is that we will be taking the first genre and production country from their respective fields. We will be assuming, for the sake of this test, that the first one listed is the primary one. So we create a separate dataframe specifically to store these temporary features.

In[36]:
chi_sq_df = pd.DataFrame()
chi_sq_df['primary_genre'] = clean_df['genres'].apply(lambda x: x.split(',')[0] if pd.notna(x) and x != '' else 'Unknown')
chi_sq_df['primary_production_country'] = clean_df['production_countries'].apply(lambda x: x.split(',')[0] if pd.notna(x) and x != '' else 'Unknown')

Then we create the contingency table:

In[37]:
contingency_table = pd.crosstab(chi_sq_df['primary_genre'], chi_sq_df['primary_production_country'])

And finally, we can run the chi-squared test.

In[38]:
chi2_stat, p_value, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
In[39]:
print(f"Chi-Squared Statistic: {chi2_stat:.4f}")
print(f"P-value: {p_value:.4f}")
print(f"Degrees of Freedom: {dof}")

Chi-Squared Statistic: 245864.1939
P-value: 0.0000
Degrees of Freedom: 4636

The following plot shows a heatmap of the residuals for the top 10 genres and production countries

In[40]:
top_10_genres = chi_sq_df[chi_sq_df['primary_genre'] != 'Unknown']['primary_genre'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index
top_10_countries = chi_sq_df[chi_sq_df['primary_production_country'] != 'Unknown']['primary_production_country'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index
filtered_df = chi_sq_df[
    chi_sq_df['primary_genre'].isin(top_10_genres) &
    chi_sq_df['primary_production_country'].isin(top_10_countries)
]

filtered_table = pd.crosstab(filtered_df['primary_genre'], filtered_df['primary_production_country'])

chi2, p, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(filtered_table)

residuals = (filtered_table - expected) / np.sqrt(expected)
sns.heatmap(residuals, fmt=".0f", cmap='coolwarm', annot=True, vmax=50, vmin=-50)
plt.title('Chi-Squared Residuals Heatmap')
plt.xlabel('Primary Production Country')
plt.ylabel('Primary Genre')
plt.show()

While the heatmap does show some of what we expect, Japan having more animations, it actually doesn't show the US having more action movies with India actually being the one having a lot more action movies than expected, it does illustrate how different countries will often specialize in certain types of media. Such as Japan making a lot more horror while make very few documentaries.

Furthermore, the p-value of 0 is well under the alpha value we chose of 0.05, meaning that there is statistically significant evidence that the primary genre and production country are not independent. Knowing that these two categorical variables are likely dependent means that if necessary, we can try to optimize our model performance by combining the genre and production_countries features into a single, interaction feature. This could help the final model have more accurate predictions. Especially since our use of a transformers embedding model, distilbert, means that combining the two columns would be relatively simple, and the additional context would actually make a significant difference in how they are embedded.

Correlation between Revenue and Vote Counts

We suspect that there is a positive relationship between revenue and vote count because the more popular a movie is, the more revenue it should make, and that popularity should also directly affect the number of votes it would get.

This idea provides us with the following hypotheses that we will test in this section.

H0: There is no correlation between a movie's revenue and its vote count.

HA: There is a positive correlation between a movie's revenue and its vote count.

We decided to first look at the correlation heatmap of all the numeric columns.

In[41]:
# Correlation heatmap for numeric columns present

    plt.xlabel('Features')
    plt.ylabel('Features')

Looking at the heatmaps, we can see that revenue and vote_count have a correlation of 0.49. This is a weak to moderate positive correlation, but we should confirm it by calculating the p-value. We also notice that vote_count and vote_average have an even higher correlation. In order to confirm that this is also statistically significant, we will also perform the test on that with the following, additional hypotheses.

H0: There is no correlation between a movie's vote average and its vote count.

HA: There is a positive correlation between a movie's vote average and its vote count.

We define our alpha to be 0.05 again.

In[42]:
alpha = 0.05

Correlation between vote_average and vote_count: 0.6757, P-value: 0.000000

Because both p-values are well below our alpha of 0.05, we have statistically significant evidence that we should reject both null hypotheses. There is support for the ideas that the correlation between revenue/vote_average and vote_count is positive.

Despite the notably high correlation coefficient between vote count and revenue/vote_average, the 2 features we will be predicting, we will still be removing vote_count. The main reason for this is that we want to use the model to predict the vote average and revenue for future movies, meaning that, we will not have vote count data for those movies. While it is a highly correlated metric, it is unfortunately not possible to use when considering future movies.

Exploratory Data Analysis Conclusion

The overall goal of our movie dataset analysis is to understand how different components of a movie, such as popularity score, date released, or movie budget, can affect the average rating and revenue of a movie, and to be able to create a model that can predict rating and revenue for future movies. In order to make full use of these metrics, we needed to turn these metrics into a usable form, formatting dates, removing extraneous columns, and embedding the text variables into dense vectors using distilbert. We then cleaned the data, removing nonsensical values, like movies with a runtime of 0, and also removing rows which lacked values that we could not fix through imputation, like the missing dates. Scaling and transforming of the data was also performed since the range of the values of the various numeric columns in our data varied quite a bit and we didn't want that to bias the final model. We also filled in missing text fields with empty strings after noticing that the missing values in the text fields were Missing at Random, and thus shouldn't be discarded.

In this exploratory analysis, we prepared our data for use in a model and dove into the data to get an overview of the relationships between the various features in our data, giving us an idea of what we are working with. This helps prepare us for the actual, full analysis of our data.

# imports for the machine learning
import torch
import torch_directml
from transformers import DistilBertTokenizer, DistilBertModel
from tqdm.notebook import tqdm
import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import torch.optim as optim
from torch.utils.data import Dataset, DataLoader
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

The main issue we face with both of our target variables, revenue and vote average, is that they are significantly zero inflated (if you want to read more on why that is an issue, click HERE). And, in the case of revenue, there are significant outliers, like Avatar or Avengers Endgame. This makes a normal regression very difficult to do since the model is likely to just predict 0 every time.

So instead of doing a normal regression, we will actually have 4 outputs instead of 2. Two of the outputs will perform the regression, but the other 2 outputs will perform a classification, they will classify whether revenue or vote average is 0 or not.

Another issue is the fact that our text embeddings are essentially 768 features (for more information on the bert model, click HERE). If we just combine this with the 25 normal features we have, these normal features will be drowned out by the text embeddings in the neural network.

What we will do to deal with that problem is we will have 2 input branches, one which will increase the dimensionality of the normal features while the other compresses the dimensionality of the text embeddings.

Lastly, because we are technically doing 2 different tasks, classification and regression, after the features are all combined together, we will have the network split apart again. One branch will be dedicated to the regression while the other will do all the classification.

In[50]:
class ZeroInflatedMultiTaskModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, text_input_dim=768, normal_input_dim=5):
        super().__init__()

        # Hyperparameters
        self.text_input_dim = text_input_dim
        self.normal_input_dim = normal_input_dim
        self.branch_output_dim = 128 # Both branches end here

        # Text Feature Reduction Branch
        # Reduces the vector dimensions
        self.text_branch = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(self.text_input_dim, 512), # Initial reduction
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(0.2),
            nn.Linear(512, self.branch_output_dim), # Final reduction
            nn.ReLU()
        )

        # Normal Feature Expansion Branch
        # Expands the vector dimensions
        self.normal_branch = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(self.normal_input_dim, 64), # Initial expansion
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(0.2),
            nn.Linear(64, self.branch_output_dim), # Final expansion
            nn.ReLU()
        )

        # Dimensions of text plus normal
        fused_dim = 2 * self.branch_output_dim

        # Trunk A For Classification Zero vs Non Zero
        self.cls_trunk = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(fused_dim, 256),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(0.3),
            nn.Linear(256, 128),
            nn.ReLU()
        )
        
        # Trunk B For Regression Value prediction
        self.reg_trunk = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(fused_dim, 256),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(0.3),
            nn.Linear(256, 128),
            nn.ReLU()
        )

        base_output_dim = 128

        # Output Heads
        # Head Revenue Classification
        self.rev_cls_head = nn.Linear(base_output_dim, 1)

        # Head Revenue Regression
        self.rev_reg_head = nn.Linear(base_output_dim, 1)

        # Head Rating Classification
        self.rate_cls_head = nn.Linear(base_output_dim, 1)

        # Head Rating Regression
        self.rate_reg_head = nn.Linear(base_output_dim, 1)

    def forward(self, text_features, normal_features):
        # Process Text Features
        text_out = self.text_branch(text_features)

        # Process Normal Features
        normal_out = self.normal_branch(normal_features)

        # Feature Fusion Concatenation
        fused_out = torch.cat([text_out, normal_out], dim=1)

        # Split Trunks
        cls_feat = self.cls_trunk(fused_out)
        reg_feat = self.reg_trunk(fused_out)

        # Output Heads
        # Revenue Classification No sigmoid because it is built into BCELoss
        rev_cls_output = self.rev_cls_head(cls_feat)

        # Revenue Regression Linear for unconstrained log scaled value
        rev_reg_output = torch.sigmoid(self.rev_reg_head(reg_feat))

        # Rating Classification No sigmoid because it is built into BCELoss
        rate_cls_output = self.rate_cls_head(cls_feat)

        # Rating Regression Sigmoid to constrain output for Min Max scaled ratings
        rate_reg_output = torch.sigmoid(self.rate_reg_head(reg_feat))

        return rev_cls_output, rev_reg_output, rate_cls_output, rate_reg_output

To avoid overfitting, make sure to include dropout layers. Other than the output neurons, all of the rest will just use ReLU as their activation function. It is both fast and sufficient for our use case here.

Custom Loss Function

Now, the difficult part here is the loss function, we can't just use a premade loss function because we have multiple types of output heads. For our classification heads, we will be using Binary Cross Entropy loss since we are just doing a simple binary classification. For the regression, we will just use MSELoss but with the caveat that the regression loss will only be calculated for training samples where the revenue or vote_average is greater than 0. Essentially, the regression will only be predicting for movies that actually made money or were actually voted on.

For those who need a reminder on what these loss functions are, these links can help provide a quick refresher: MSE Loss and BCE Loss.

These losses will then be combined according to the 4 new hyperparameters we are adding, called the "loss weights". So our total loss will be:

$L = \lambda_1 \cdot L_1 + \lambda_2 \cdot L_2 + \lambda_3 \cdot L_3 + \lambda_4 \cdot L_4$

In[51]:
def train_model(model, data_loader, optimizer, loss_weights, device):
    model.train()

    bce_rev_loss_fn = nn.BCEWithLogitsLoss()
    bce_rate_loss_fn = nn.BCEWithLogitsLoss()
    reg_loss_fn = nn.MSELoss() # For regression Heads 2 & 4

    total_loss = 0

    progress_bar = tqdm(data_loader, desc=f"Current Epoch: ", leave=True)

    for text_feats, normal_feats, target_rev, target_rate in progress_bar:
        # Move data to the appropriate device CPU GPU
        text_feats = text_feats.to(device, non_blocking=True)
        normal_feats = normal_feats.to(device, non_blocking=True)
        target_rev = target_rev.to(device, non_blocking=True)
        target_rate = target_rate.to(device, non_blocking=True)

        optimizer.zero_grad()

        # Get model predictions
        pred_rev_cls, pred_rev_reg, pred_rate_cls, pred_rate_reg = model(text_feats, normal_feats)

        # Revenue Loss

        # Classification Loss P(Revenue > 0)
        # Create binary target 1 if target > 0, 0 otherwise
        target_rev_cls = (target_rev > 0).float()
        loss_rev_cls = bce_rev_loss_fn(pred_rev_cls.squeeze(), target_rev_cls)

        # Regression Loss Only for non zero targets
        # Create a mask for non zero revenue targets
        rev_mask = (target_rev > 0).squeeze()

        # Apply mask to predictions and targets
        if rev_mask.any():
            loss_rev_reg = reg_loss_fn(
                pred_rev_reg.squeeze()[rev_mask],
                target_rev.squeeze()[rev_mask]
            )
        else:
            loss_rev_reg = torch.tensor(0.0, device=device)

        # Rating Loss

        # Classification Loss P(Rating > 0)
        target_rate_cls = (target_rate > 0).float()
        loss_rate_cls = bce_rate_loss_fn(pred_rate_cls.squeeze(), target_rate_cls)

        # Regression Loss Only for non zero targets
        rate_mask = (target_rate > 0).squeeze()

        # Apply mask to predictions and targets
        if rate_mask.any():
            loss_rate_reg = reg_loss_fn(
                pred_rate_reg.squeeze()[rate_mask],
                target_rate.squeeze()[rate_mask]
            )
        else:
            loss_rate_reg = torch.tensor(0.0, device=device)

        # Total Weighted Loss
        total_loss_batch = (
            loss_weights[0] * loss_rev_cls +
            loss_weights[1] * loss_rev_reg +
            loss_weights[2] * loss_rate_cls +
            loss_weights[3] * loss_rate_reg
        )

        # Backward pass and optimization
        total_loss_batch.backward()
        torch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(model.parameters(), max_norm=1.0)
        optimizer.step()

        current_loss = total_loss_batch.item()
        total_loss += total_loss_batch.item()

        progress_bar.set_postfix({'batch_loss': f'{current_loss:.4f}'})

    return total_loss / len(data_loader)

Now we will create the Dataset class, we will store our data as numpy arrays for efficiency.

In[52]:
class ZeroInflatedMultiTaskDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, X_text, X_normal, y_revenue, y_rating):
        # Convert all pandas data to numpy float32
        # Features
        if isinstance(X_text, pd.Series):
            X_text = np.stack(X_text.values).astype(np.float32)
        self.text_feats = np.array(X_text, dtype=np.float32)

        self.normal_feats = np.array(X_normal.values, dtype=np.float32)

        # Targets
        self.target_rev = np.array(y_revenue.values, dtype=np.float32)
        self.target_rate = np.array(y_rating.values, dtype=np.float32)

        # Verify matching lengths just in case
        assert len(self.text_feats) == len(self.normal_feats) == len(self.target_rev)

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.text_feats)

    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        # The order must match the expected order in the train_model function:
        # text_feats, normal_feats, target_rev, target_rate
        return (
            self.text_feats[idx],
            self.normal_feats[idx],
            self.target_rev[idx],
            self.target_rate[idx]
        )

In order to make sure our model sees enough non-zero revenue training samples, we will implement weighted sampling. This way, in each batch, the model will see a 50/50 split of non-zero revenue and zero revenue samples.

In[63]:
from torch.utils.data import WeightedRandomSampler

# Weight for class 0
weight_0 = 1.0 / count_zeros
# Weight for class 1
weight_1 = 1.0 / count_ones

# 2. Assign a weight to every single sample in the training set
sample_weights = np.where(y_rev_train > 0, weight_1, weight_0)

# 3. Convert to Tensor
sample_weights = torch.from_numpy(sample_weights).double()

# 4. Create the Sampler
sampler = WeightedRandomSampler(
    weights=sample_weights,
    num_samples=len(sample_weights),
    replacement=True
)

Evaluation of Model Performance

Something important for our model, is that because of the way it is set up, the threshold for the classification can't be 0.5. In order to find the "optimal" threshold, basically the threshold which maximizes the f1 score, the following code has been provided.

Though, it is important to note that depending on the use case, it might be better to maximize recall or precision rather than f1-score.

In[67]:
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score, precision_score, recall_score
import numpy as np
import torch

def optimize_threshold(y_true, y_probs, task_name="Classification"):
    """
    Helper function to iterate over thresholds and find the best F1 score.
    """
    print("\n" + "="*40)
    print(f"{task_name.upper()} - THRESHOLD OPTIMIZATION (F1-Score)")
    print("="*40)
    
    best_thresh = 0
    best_f1 = 0
    
    # Test thresholds from 0.05 to 0.95
    for thresh in np.arange(0.05, 0.96, 0.01):
        preds = (np.array(y_probs) > thresh).astype(int)
        
        # Calculate metrics
        score = f1_score(y_true, preds, zero_division=0)
        prec = precision_score(y_true, preds, zero_division=0)
        rec = recall_score(y_true, preds, zero_division=0)
        
        # Print row
        if int((thresh * 100) % 10) == 0:
            print(f"Thresh {thresh:.2f} | F1: {score:.4f} | Prec: {prec:.4f} | Recall: {rec:.4f}")
        
        # Track best
        if score > best_f1:
            best_f1 = score
            best_thresh = thresh
            
    print(f"\nOptimal {task_name} Threshold: {best_thresh:.2f} (Max F1: {best_f1:.4f})")
    return best_thresh

def advanced_evaluation(model, data_loader, device, minmax_scaler):
    model.eval()
    
    # Revenue Regression
    true_rev_vals = [] 
    pred_rev_vals = [] 
    
    # Revenue Classification
    true_rev_cls = []
    pred_rev_probs = []

    # Rating Classification
    true_rate_cls = []
    pred_rate_probs = []

    with torch.no_grad():
        for text_feats, normal_feats, target_rev, target_rate in data_loader:
            text_feats = text_feats.to(device, non_blocking=True)
            normal_feats = normal_feats.to(device, non_blocking=True)
            
            # Forward Pass
            p_rev_cls, p_rev_reg, p_rate_cls, p_rate_reg = model(text_feats, normal_feats)
            
            # Collect Revenue Classification Data
            probs_rev = torch.sigmoid(p_rev_cls).cpu().numpy().flatten()
            pred_rev_probs.extend(probs_rev)
            true_rev_cls.extend((target_rev.cpu().numpy() > 0).astype(int))

            # Collect Rating Classification Data
            probs_rate = torch.sigmoid(p_rate_cls).cpu().numpy().flatten()
            pred_rate_probs.extend(probs_rate)
            true_rate_cls.extend((target_rate.cpu().numpy() > 0).astype(int))

            # Collect Revenue Regression Data (Only for Actual > 0)
            mask = target_rev.cpu().numpy() > 0
            if mask.any():
                # Get raw 0-1 predictions
                p_reg = p_rev_reg.cpu().numpy().flatten()[mask]
                t_reg = target_rev.cpu().numpy()[mask]
                
                # Reshape for scaler
                p_reshaped = p_reg.reshape(-1, 1)
                t_reshaped = t_reg.reshape(-1, 1)
                
                # Inverse MinMax -> Inverse Log
                p_log = minmax_scaler.inverse_transform(p_reshaped)
                t_log = minmax_scaler.inverse_transform(t_reshaped)
                
                pred_rev_vals.extend(np.expm1(p_log).flatten())
                true_rev_vals.extend(np.expm1(t_log).flatten())
    
    # Revenue Classification Threshold
    rev_thresh = optimize_threshold(true_rev_cls, pred_rev_probs, task_name="Revenue")

    # Rating Classification Threshold
    rate_thresh = optimize_threshold(true_rate_cls, pred_rate_probs, task_name="Rating")

    return rev_thresh, rate_thresh

The next bit of code helps you evaluate the performance of the model by printing some useful metrics. "evaluate_model" is a function that will help take the output from the model and make it usable for analysis. One of the main things is that it performs the sigmoid on the output from the classification heads (which is missing from the model due to the usage of BCE with logits loss which has a built in sigmoid) before classifying the results according to the threshold you pass in.

In[68]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error, confusion_matrix, roc_auc_score, classification_report, median_absolute_error

def evaluate_model(model, data_loader, device, rev_thresh, rate_thresh):
    model.eval()
    
    results = {
        'rev_cls_true': [], 'rev_cls_pred': [], 'rev_cls_prob': [],
        'rev_reg_true': [], 'rev_reg_pred': [],
        'rate_cls_true': [], 'rate_cls_pred': [], 'rate_cls_prob': [],
        'rate_reg_true': [], 'rate_reg_pred': []
    }

    with torch.no_grad():
        for text_feats, normal_feats, target_rev, target_rate in data_loader:
            text_feats = text_feats.to(device, non_blocking=True)
            normal_feats = normal_feats.to(device, non_blocking=True)
            
            # Forward pass
            p_rev_cls, p_rev_reg, p_rate_cls, p_rate_reg = model(text_feats, normal_feats)

            # Process Predictions
            
            # Revenue Classification 
            rev_probs = torch.sigmoid(p_rev_cls).cpu().numpy().flatten()
            results['rev_cls_prob'].extend(rev_probs)
            results['rev_cls_pred'].extend((rev_probs > rev_thresh).astype(int))
            results['rev_cls_true'].extend((target_rev.cpu().numpy() > 0).astype(int))

            # Revenue Regression 
            results['rev_reg_pred'].extend(p_rev_reg.cpu().numpy().flatten())
            results['rev_reg_true'].extend(target_rev.cpu().numpy())

            # Rating Classification
            rate_probs = torch.sigmoid(p_rate_cls).cpu().numpy().flatten()
            results['rate_cls_prob'].extend(rate_probs)
            results['rate_cls_pred'].extend((rate_probs > rate_thresh).astype(int))
            results['rate_cls_true'].extend((target_rate.cpu().numpy() > 0).astype(int))

            # Rating Regression
            results['rate_reg_pred'].extend(p_rate_reg.cpu().numpy().flatten())
            results['rate_reg_true'].extend(target_rate.cpu().numpy())

    return {k: np.array(v) for k, v in results.items()}

def print_metrics(results, rev_scaler):
    print("="*40)
    print("      MODEL PERFORMANCE REPORT")
    print("="*40)
    
    # Revenue Classification
    acc_rev = accuracy_score(results['rev_cls_true'], results['rev_cls_pred'])
    auc_rev = roc_auc_score(results['rev_cls_true'], results['rev_cls_prob'])
    print(f"\n[Head 1] Revenue Classification (Zero vs Non-Zero):")
    print(f"  Accuracy: {acc_rev:.4f}")
    print(f"  AUC-ROC:  {auc_rev:.4f}")

    print(classification_report(results['rev_cls_true'], results['rev_cls_pred']))
    
    # Revenue Regression
    # Only evaluate regression on items that actually had revenue > 0
    mask_rev = results['rev_reg_true'] > 0 
    if mask_rev.sum() > 0:
        pred_0to1 = results['rev_reg_pred'][mask_rev]
        true_0to1 = results['rev_reg_true'][mask_rev]
        
        mse = mean_squared_error(true_0to1, pred_0to1)
        print(f"\n[Head 2] Revenue Regression:")
        print(f"  MSE (0-1 Scale): {mse:.4f}")

        pred_reshaped = pred_0to1.reshape(-1, 1)
        true_reshaped = true_0to1.reshape(-1, 1)
        
        # Recover the original input to the scaler
        pred_log = rev_scaler.inverse_transform(pred_reshaped)
        true_log = rev_scaler.inverse_transform(true_reshaped)
        
        # Log -> Dollars
        pred_dollars = np.expm1(pred_log)
        true_dollars = np.expm1(true_log)
        
        mae = median_absolute_error(true_dollars, pred_dollars)
        print(f"  Median Absolute Error (Dollars): ${mae:,.2f}")

    # Rating Classification
    acc_rate = accuracy_score(results['rate_cls_true'], results['rate_cls_pred'])
    print(f"\n[Head 3] Rating Classification (Rated vs Unrated):")
    print(f"  Accuracy: {acc_rate:.4f}")

    print(classification_report(results['rate_cls_true'], results['rate_cls_pred']))
    
    # Rating Regression
    mask_rate = results['rate_reg_true'] > 0
    if mask_rate.sum() > 0:
        true_rate = results['rate_reg_true'][mask_rate]
        pred_rate = results['rate_reg_pred'][mask_rate]
        
        mae_rate = mean_absolute_error(true_rate, pred_rate)
        
        print(f"\n[Head 4] Rating Regression:")
        print(f"  MAE: {mae_rate:.4f} (Scale 0-1)")
    else:
        print("\n[Head 4] No non-zero rating samples in test set.")

def plot_performance(results):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(15, 12))
    
    # Revenue Classification Confusion Matrix
    cm_rev = confusion_matrix(results['rev_cls_true'], results['rev_cls_pred'])
    sns.heatmap(cm_rev, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', ax=axes[0,0])
    axes[0,0].set_title('Revenue Classification Confusion Matrix (0 or non-zero)')
    axes[0,0].set_xlabel('Predicted')
    axes[0,0].set_ylabel('Actual')

    #Revenue Regression (Actual vs Predicted Log)
    mask_rev = results['rev_reg_true'] > 0
    axes[0,1].scatter(results['rev_reg_true'][mask_rev], results['rev_reg_pred'][mask_rev], alpha=0.5, s=5)
    # Plot identity line
    min_val = min(results['rev_reg_true'].min(), results['rev_reg_pred'].min())
    max_val = max(results['rev_reg_true'].max(), results['rev_reg_pred'].max())
    axes[0,1].plot([min_val, max_val], [min_val, max_val], 'r--')
    axes[0,1].set_title('Revenue Regression (Log Scale)')
    axes[0,1].set_xlabel('Actual Log Revenue')
    axes[0,1].set_ylabel('Predicted Log Revenue')

    # Rating Classification Confusion Matrix
    cm_rate = confusion_matrix(results['rate_cls_true'], results['rate_cls_pred'])
    sns.heatmap(cm_rate, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Greens', ax=axes[1,0])
    axes[1,0].set_title('Rating Classification Confusion Matrix (0 or non-zero)')
    axes[1,0].set_xlabel('Predicted')
    axes[1,0].set_ylabel('Actual')

    # Rating Regression (Actual vs Predicted)
    mask_rate = results['rate_reg_true'] > 0
    axes[1,1].scatter(results['rate_reg_true'][mask_rate], results['rate_reg_pred'][mask_rate], alpha=0.5, s=1, color='green')
    axes[1,1].plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'r--')
    axes[1,1].set_title('Rating Regression (Scaled 0-1)')
    axes[1,1].set_xlabel('Actual Rating')
    axes[1,1].set_ylabel('Predicted Rating')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Insights and Conclusions

The overall goal of our movie dataset analysis is to understand how different components of a movie, such as popularity score, date released, or movie budget, can affect the average rating and revenue of a movie, and to be able to create a model that can predict rating and revenue for future movies. In order to make full use of these metrics, we needed to turn these metrics into a usable form, formatting dates, removing extraneous columns, and embedding the text variables into dense vectors using distilbert. We then cleaned the data, removing nonsensical values, like movies with a runtime of 0, and also removing rows which lacked values that we could not fix through imputation, like the missing dates. Scaling and transforming of the data was also performed since the range of the values of the various numeric columns in our data varied quite a bit and we didnt want that to bias the final model. We also filled in missing text fields with empty strings after noticing that the missing values in the text fields were Missing at Random, and thus shouldnt be discarded.

What we found through this process is that using relatively basic features you can actually build a model that can relatively, reliably predict movie revenues and vote averages. Despite the significant challenges of the zero-inflated targets to the classification, the regression part of the model managed to remain quite reliable.

If we could further extend our work, we would want to add other, very important features, like marketing budget, famous actors in the cast, directors, etc. Many of these features would likely be highly correlated with a movie's revenue and rating, especially marketing budget. The fact that our model performed as well as it did without such important features is quite interesting.
